explanation:
Here’s a clear overview of the **most commonly used data structures** in modern JavaScript (2024–2026 era), with short explanations and practical examples.

| #  | Data Structure          | Built-in?     | Ordered? | Allows duplicates? | Fastest operation          | Typical use case                              | Example (code)                                      |
|---|--------------------------|---------------|----------|---------------------|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| 1  | Array                   | Yes           | Yes      | Yes                 | Access O(1), push/pop O(1) | Ordered lists, stacks, queues (with tricks)   | `let arr = [10, "hi", {x:1}, true];`               |
| 2  | Object (as key-value)   | Yes           | Insertion (since 2015) | Keys unique        | Access ~O(1)               | General purpose dictionary / hash map         | `let obj = { name: "Alex", age: 28, active: true };` |
| 3  | Map                     | Yes (ES6)     | Insertion order | Yes (values)       | ~O(1) get/set              | When keys can be anything (not just strings)  | `let m = new Map(); m.set(obj, 42); m.set("key", "value");` |
| 4  | Set                     | Yes (ES6)     | Insertion order | No                 | ~O(1) has/add/delete       | Unique values, membership testing             | `let s = new Set([1,2,2,3]); // → Set {1,2,3}`     |
| 5  | WeakMap                 | Yes           | —        | —                   | ~O(1)                      | Private data, caching with DOM nodes / objects| `let wm = new WeakMap(); wm.set(someEl, data);`    |
| 6  | WeakSet                 | Yes           | —        | No                  | ~O(1) has/add/delete       | Tracking unique objects without preventing GC | `let ws = new WeakSet(); ws.add(someObj);`         |
| 7  | Stack                   | No (pattern)  | Yes      | Yes                 | push/pop O(1)              | Undo/redo, call stack, expression evaluation  | `const stack = []; stack.push(1); stack.pop();`    |
| 8  | Queue                   | No (pattern)  | Yes      | Yes                 | enqueue O(1), dequeue O(1) | Task scheduling, BFS, print queue             | `const q = []; q.push(5); q.shift();`              |
| 9  | Deque (Double-ended queue) | No         | Yes      | Yes                 | O(1) both ends             | Sliding window, palindrome check, scheduler   | Use array + `push/unshift/pop/shift` carefully     |
| 10 | Linked List             | No            | Yes      | Yes                 | Insert/delete O(1) if you have node | (rare in JS) – when frequent middle inserts  | Custom class (see below)                           |
| 11 | Binary Search Tree      | No            | —        | Usually no          | O(log n) avg, O(n) worst   | Sorted data, range queries (without library)  | Custom implementation                              |
| 12 | Heap / Priority Queue   | No            | —        | Yes                 | O(log n) insert/extract    | Dijkstra, task scheduler, top-k problems      | Libraries or custom binary heap                    |
| 13 | Trie (Prefix Tree)      | No            | —        | —                   | O(length) prefix search    | Autocomplete, spell checker, IP routing       | Custom implementation                              |
| 14 | Graph                   | No            | —        | —                   | —                          | Social networks, maps, dependencies           | Adjacency list: `Map<number, number[]>`            |

### Quick code examples – most useful ones

```js
// 1. Array (most used)
const tasks = ["learn", "code", "sleep"];
tasks.push("eat");           // add end
tasks.unshift("wake up");    // add start
tasks.pop();                 // remove end
console.log(tasks[1]);       // random access

// 2. Object vs Map
const obj = { 123: "numeric key" };          // key becomes string "123"
const map = new Map();
map.set(123, "numeric key");                 // key stays number
console.log(map.get(123));                   // works

// 3. Set – unique values
const uniqueIds = new Set();
uniqueIds.add(7).add(7).add("7");
console.log(uniqueIds.size);                 // 2
console.log(uniqueIds.has(7));               // true

// 4. Very simple Linked List (for interviews)
class Node {
  constructor(val) {
    this.val = val;
    this.next = null;
  }
}

class LinkedList {
  constructor() {
    this.head = null;
    this.tail = null;
    this.length = 0;
  }
  push(val) {
    const node = new Node(val);
    if (!this.head) {
      this.head = this.tail = node;
    } else {
      this.tail.next = node;
      this.tail = node;
    }
    this.length++;
    return this;
  }
}

// 5. Graph – adjacency list (very common pattern)
const graph = new Map();
graph.set("A", ["B", "C"]);
graph.set("B", ["A", "D"]);
graph.set("C", ["A"]);
graph.set("D", ["B"]);

// 6. Priority Queue – many people use a simple sorted array for small data
// or a proper binary heap library / implementation for serious work
```

### Quick decision guide (2025+ JS)

- Need **key → value** and keys are strings/symbols → **Object**
- Keys can be objects/numbers/functions → **Map**
- Want **only unique values** → **Set**
- Need **fast membership test** on primitives → **Set**
- Need **ordered list + random access** → **Array**
- Need **LIFO** (last in first out) → Array `.push()` + `.pop()`
- Need **FIFO** (first in first out) → Array `.push()` + `.shift()` (or look at libraries)
- Need **real performance-critical graph/heap/tree** → usually use a library (e.g. graphology, heap-js, etc.)

